# <a id="_56pokwijgb1j"></a>Forward

#### <a id="_wv1gd8cqe447"></a>__Central Messages__

1. Jesus means SALVATION\.  Regardless of what form SALVATION takes place\.  Those who believe in Jesus’ name \(even as a meaningless sound\) will receive eternal rest, as promised\.  Blessed are the poor in spirit\.  But those who believe in the meaning of SALVATION, and seek it in any of its forms,  invention, medicine, forgiveness, or teaching will bring God’s Kingdom to earth\.
2. The correct way to read the gospels is by using all four of them\.  When there are differences, acknowledge them\.  When there are similarities, emphasize them\.  I have used __Boldfaced for Matthew__, underline for Mark, *Italics for Luke*, Red for John\.
3. Jesus \(Son of Man\) and Jesus \(of Nazareth\) have two different roles\.  The Son of Man is required to warn humanity of all the sins that we can die from\.  If people sin, and die from their sins, and the Son of Man has not warned them, then the Son of Man will be held accountable by God\.
4. John wrote new stories about Barabbas after he died\.  In Ezekiel, the Son of Man is asked by God to build a model of Jerusalem, and cook his food \(scripture\) over human feces\.   But John continues in this tradition, building a model of Jerusalem in his mind, and uses essentially a sock\-puppet of Jesus Barabbas to preach to Jerusalem\.  Some of the events in John and Luke appear to be based on Jesus Barabbas\.
5.  Barabbas took the role of the Son of Man, but by dying without warning anyone about anything, he was held accountable by God for ALL SIN\.  “Don’t worry\.  I got this\!”  
6. Though one witness saw Jesus of Nazareth stabbed to death by Pilate’s soldier, this is not enough to convict Pilate, Herod, or the Jews of killing the Messiah according to Jewish Law\.  However, since the blood of Barabbas was put on his forehead, Jesus Anointed \(Christ\) became the door for the Christians\.  When the blood of the lamb was placed on his forehead, this means that all who believe that Jesus of Nazareth is the Way \(Door\) are protected like the Egyptians who do not keep the Passover
7. The living Jesus told the women to tell his disciples to meet him in Galilee\.  Those who did not ignore the women found Jesus in Galilee saying “Baptize all nations in the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit\.”  Those that ignored the women found false prophets in the wilderness and behind closed doors\.
8. While it is up to the Jews to decide whether Jesus of Nazareth is their messiah, Jesus, Son of Man, Barabbas, is definitely NOT their Messiah\.  The Messiah’s role is not the same as the Son of Man\.  The Messiah’s role is to teach righteousness\.  The Son of Man’s role is the same as that of AZAZEL, the goat, to have all the sins of Israel confessed over his head\.
9. There are some Greek myths hidden here and there in the gospels\. 

#### <a id="_e612jqo2q45v"></a>__Greek Myth__

Tiresias struck at two snakes copulating \(Ophiuchus\) and Hera punished him by turning him into a woman\.  For seven years he lived as a woman and bore a daughter, Mantos \(which means prophetess\)\.  Mantos was taken as the spoils of war, and Apollo took her as his lover\.  Tiresias went back to the same place seven years later, and struck the fish \(Pisces\) at the same position\.  Hera asked Tiresias a question:  “Which is better, to live as a man or a woman?”  And Tiresias said “Of ten parts, man enjoys only one\.”  To prove just how incorrect he was, Hera cursed Tiresias with blindness\.  But while he was blind, he gained the gift of hearing prophecy in the sound of birdsong\.  When Tiresias died, he went to the land of the dead…  This land, in Sidon, was ruled by Melqart, the daughter of Astarte\.  When Odysseus visited the land of the dead, he did not see Melqart, but Tiresias\.  Tiresias said to Odysseus, “Take an oar inland until someone mistakes it for a winnowing fan\.  There you shall build a temple to Poseidon\.”  As soon as Jesus came into Sidon, Astarte knew he had entered the house of Pisces, and came to him and said, “Lord, come help, because my daughter is sick\.  She is inhabited by an impure Spirit\.”  Jesus said to Astarte, it is not fit for the gods to take the food of the little children of Israel\.  But Astarte said “Even the dogs eat the food that falls from the Master’s table\.”  And Jesus said to her, “Woman, you have great faith\.  For this answer, go, your daughter is healed\.”  Mantos was captured from Thebes by Assyria, and as the Spoils of war, she was taken at the Mount of Olives in Delphi by Apollo, Maher Shalal Hash Baz\.  The Oar of Tiresias was carried by John the Baptist, who took it as baptism, an oar for salvation of all who would use it\.  When he passed, the oar went to John the Apostle, who treated the baptism as a winnowing fan, placing a gnostic requirement on Salvation\-\-belief in the name of God’s only Son\.  Then Herod and Pilate put a Crown of Thorns, and the Robes of Odysseus on Jesus of Nazareth, and placed the blood of Elijah on his forehead, thus dedicating the Christ as the temple of Poseidon\.

21 “Lord,” ARIES said to SPRING SOLSTICE, “if you had been here, my brother would not have died\. 22 But I know that even now God will give you whatever you ask\.”

23 SPRING SOLSTICE said to her, “Your brother will rise again\.”

24 ARIES answered, “I know he will rise again in the resurrection at the last day\.”

25 SPRING SOLSTICE said to her, “I am the resurrection and the life\. The one who believes in me will live, even though they die; 26 and whoever lives by believing in me will never die\. Do you believe this?”

27 “Yes, Lord,” she replied, “I believe that you are the Messiah, the Son of God, who is to come into the world\.”

28 After she had said this, she went back and called her sister PISCES aside\. “The Teacher is here,” she said, “and is asking for you\.” 29 When PISCES heard this, she got up quickly and went to him\. 30 Now SPRING SOLSTICE had not yet entered the village, but was still at the place where ARIES had met him\. 31 When the Jews who had been with PISCES in the house, comforting her, noticed how quickly she got up and went out, they followed her, supposing she was going to the tomb to mourn there\.

32 When PISCES reached the place where SPRING SOLSTICE was and saw him, she fell at his feet and said, “Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died\.”

33 When SPRING SOLSTICE saw her weeping, and the Jews who had come along with her also weeping, he was deeply moved in spirit and troubled\. 34 “Where have you laid him?” he asked\.

“Come and see, Lord,” they replied\.

35 SPRING SOLSTICE wept\.

36 Then the Jews said, “See how he loved him\!”

37 But some of them said, “Could not he who opened the eyes of the blind man have kept this man from dying?”

“But, Lord,” said ARIES, the sister of the dead man, “by this time there is a bad odor, for he has been there four MILLENIA\.”

40 Then SPRING SOLSTICE said, “Did I not tell you that if you believe, you will see the glory of God?”

41 So they took away the stone\. Then SPRING SOLSTICE looked up and said, “Father, I thank you that you have heard me\. 42 I knew that you always hear me, but I said this for the benefit of the people standing here, that they may believe that you sent me\.”

#### <a id="_e48txwjqt3ee"></a>__John 4: Draupadi at the Well__

Question:  “Why do we not know the name of the woman at the well?”

Thanks for asking this question\. You made me ask it myself\. Ask, seek, knock, and you will find\. I hope this gives no offense to anyone\. My knowledge of Hindu myth is fairly scant, and I have mostly just gathered this from googling and Microsoft Copilot help\.

Draupadi is a significant figure in Hindu mythology\. She is revered for her unwavering adherence to duty, and her devotion to Lord Krishna\. Krishna is known for his roles as protector, compassionate being, and divine hero\.

Krishna is known for mischievous pranks and miraculous deeds in his youth\. Hid divine love with Radha, and enchanting flute\. And finally as a charioteer and guide, he offered his spiritual wisdom to Arjuna in the Bhagavad Gita\. His teachings emphasize devotion, righteousness, and the importance of performing one's duty without attachment to the results\.

In Draupadi's fourth incarnation, she prayed to Krishna for a perfect husband\.

Krishna granted his request, but by giving her five different husbands, each with one of the five attributes that she requested\.

1\. He would be a symbol of Dharma\. She wanted him to have an unwavering adherence to duty and righteousness\.

2\. He would be strong as God Hanuman\. \(She wanted him to have immense strength and bravery\.\)

3\. He would be skilled in Archery as God Parashurama\. \(She wanted him to have exceptional archery skills\.\)

4\. He would be intelligent as Deva Guru Brihaspati\. \(And to be known for his wisdom and knowledge\.\)

5\. He would be the most handsome man on the earth\. \(Exceptional skills with a sword\.\)

Draupadi was from Panchala, in India, so she was not literally a Samaritan woman, but as for the Metaphorical meaning of "A good Samaritan" Draupadi was a charitable and helpful person\.

In Hindu mythology, Draupadi is considered one of the Panchakanya \(five virgins\), and she is often associated with the concept of reincarnation\. According to some traditions, Draupadi is believed to be an incarnation of Goddess Shree or Mahalakshmi, the goddess of wealth and prosperity\. However, specific details about her fifth incarnation are not commonly found in mainstream texts\.

If we imagined crossover\-mythology where Jesus met with Her five husbands, Yudhishthira, Bhima, Arjuna, Nakula, and Sahadeva,

Jesus \(Son of Man\) immediately knew Draupadi, and knew that she had five husbands\. And he said "The man you have now is not your husband," meaning, the Messiah called Christ \(Son of Man\) is not one of the five men that Draupadi prayed for\.

Draupadi could see that Jesus was a prophet\.

Now Draupadi had a chamber where she was to spend one year with each of her husbands\. But it was forbidden for anyone else to enter the chamber, even accidentally\. If anyone entered the chamber, they were to be exiled for a whole year\.

So Jesus entered the chamber, for two days\. Jesus Barabbas entered on the last day of Nakula, , known for his swordsmanship and handsome appearance\.  \(He taught Nakula a few last tricks to try with his sword…\) Jesus of Nazareth entered on the first day of Sahadeva\. Sahadeva came in; the youngest, known for his wisdom\.  Both men thought that Jesus was the savior of the world\.

Once Draupadi's husbands heard what Jesus had to say, they believed that Jesus was the savior of the world\.

But on the day that Wisdom leaves Draupadi's chambers, Jesus Barabbas and Jesus of Nazareth are ready for the salvation of the world\.
